\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Matrix-Multiplication"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 To recap using the new notation,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{w})\bcdot\mathbf{v} & =\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}+\mathbf{w}\bcdot\mathbf{v}\\
 & \text{and}\\
(c\mathbf{u})\bcdot\mathbf{v} & =c(\mathbf{u}\bcdot\mathbf{v}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Can you show these identities are true using properties of real numbers?
 Answer on page 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand pageref
reference "ans:dot-product-identities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 You might think of these properties as a kind of linearity.
 Since they follow as a natural consequence of using real number scalars,
 any abstraction of the dot product should have a similar distributive and
 associative properties.
\end_layout

