\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
We use the words norm instead of magnitude (or length) and orthogonal instead
 of perpendicular because magnitude and perpendicular have special, visual,
 geometric meaning in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 that does not readily transer to other contexts.
 Objects such as matrices and functions, and even vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>3$
\end_inset

 cannot be visualized the same way.
 What would it mean for two polynomials to be perpendicular, for example?
 What would be the geometric magnitude (or length) of a matrix? The familiar
 geometric notions of length and perpendicularity of vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}$
\end_inset

 have no geometric analogy in other vector spaces such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{P}_{2}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}_{m\times n}(\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

.
 No matter.
 This is really the purpose of the above chart.
 Orthogonality (the abstraction of perpendicularity) of two vectors is 
\shape italic
defined by
\shape default
 the requirement that their inner product be zero whatever that may look
 like geometrically.
 Therein lies the power of mathematical abstraction.
 A notion such as perpendicularity, which we can clearly see and grasp in
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, can be extended to other sets where no analogous picture can be drawn.
 Likewise the norm (abstraction of length) of a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is 
\shape italic
defined by
\shape default
 the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\langle M,M\rangle}$
\end_inset

 whether it has geometric meaning or not.
\end_layout

